    <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">The Problem of Toxic Comments on Wikipedia</h2>
    <p class="mb-4 font-serif text-xl text-gray-700">Platforms that aggregate user content are the foundation of knowledge sharing on the Internet. But not all people on the Internet are interested in participating nicely, and some see it as an avenue to vent their rage, insecurity, and prejudices. This is particularly evident on Wikipedia, which runs on user-generated content and is dependent on user discussion to curate and approve content. Unfortunately, some users abuse this privilege by posting toxic comments.</p>
    <p class="mb-4 font-serif text-xl text-gray-700">To maintain a positive community, toxic content and the users posting it need to be removed quickly. However, Wikipedia doesn't have the resources to hire full-time moderators to review every comment. This is where natural language processing can help.</p>
    <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-bold">The Need for a Classification System</h3>
    <p class="mb-4 font-serif text-xl text-gray-700">To address the problem of toxic comments on Wikipedia, our team of Navneet, Samakash, and Manish developed a classification system using natural language processing. The system uses a large open dataset of labeled Wikipedia Talk Page comments, provided by the Conversation AI team owned by Alphabet.</p>
    <p class="mb-4 font-serif text-xl text-gray-700">The dataset has six labels that represent subcategories of toxicity, but our project focuses on a seventh label that represents the general toxicity of the comments. By classifying comments as toxic or non-toxic, we can identify and remove toxic comments more efficiently, thereby maintaining a more positive community on Wikipedia.</p>
  </div>
